Want to cross-verify your identity on Mastodon but don't have your own website? 

If you're on GitHub, you can set up something similar with GitHub Pages

1. Add simple index.html file to GitHub repo
2. Enable GitHub Pages in Settings
3. Link in Mastodon profile

text:
There are two problems with ROC curves

‚ùå They don't work for imbalanced datasets
‚ùå They don't work for object detection problems

So what do we do to evaluate our machine learning models properly in these cases?

We use a Precision-Recall curve.

Use colorblind friendly palettes. Avoid Red-Green.

text:
Most common help I supply to colleagues fitting multilevel models? Non-centered priors.

This:
mu <- a[id]
a[id] ~ normal( abar , sigma )

Becomes:
mu <- abar + z[id]*sigma
z[id] ~ normal( 0 , 1 )

Explained in Ch 13 of my book, also this old blog post: https://t.co/IouhY0iT2E
full_text:

text:
#Rose
library(tidyverse)
seq(-4,4,by=.012) %>%
  expand.grid(x=., y=.) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=(1-abs(x)-sin(y^2)), y=(1+y-cos(x^2)))) +
  geom_point(alpha=.03, shape=20, size=0)+
  theme_void()+
  coord_polar()

#rstats #maths #creativecoding https://t.co/ccmiPoIhv2

1/

text:
Learning about Bayesian IRT (https://t.co/3N0PTNmxlc) and am intrigued how, with multiple items, the model decomposition yields person- and item-specific results. 

Is it correct that one could return person-specific effect sizes in a 2-time point trial with this method?

#brms
full_text:
Learning about Bayesian IRT (https://t.co/3N0PTNmxlc) and am intrigued how, with multiple items, the model decomposition yields person- and item-specific results. 

Is it correct that one could return person-specific effect sizes in a 2-time point trial with this method?

#brms

text:
@BenjaminWolfe Nice. Reminds me of this similar trick for ggplot:

ggplot(df, aes(x, y)) +
  geom_point() +
  (lots of other lines) +
  NULL

By putting a NULL at the end, can comment out any combination of lines and it still runs fine.
full_text:
@BenjaminWolfe Nice. Reminds me of this similar trick for ggplot:

ggplot(df, aes(x, y)) +
  geom_point() +
  (lots of other lines) +
  NULL

By putting a NULL at the end, can comment out any combination of lines and it still runs fine.

text:
Multithreading works in rstan 2.18.1 @mcmc_stan now. Need a new flag in Makevars:
$ cd ~/.R
$ echo "PKG_CXXFLAGS += -DSTAN_THREADS" >> Makevars
And in R session, set thread count:
> Sys.setenv(STAN_NUM_THREADS=4)
https://t.co/jy09yRDvFK
full_text:

And in R session, set thread count:

Surprisingly cogent meditation on probabilistic thinking in the NYT. 

Takeaways:

1. People round probabilities up to 100% or down to 0%.

2. People call probability ‚Äúwrong‚Äù if <50% events happen

 3. People need a story to take <50% scenarios seriously
